            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Nikolai Reyes is a product of the Bay Area\u2019s confluence of cultures. Born in Daly City to a Filipino-American father, a union mechanic for BART, and a Russian immigrant mother who worked as a caregiver, Nikolai\u2019s childhood was a blend of lumpia and borscht, Tagalog phrases and Russian lullabies. He grew up acutely aware of movement. He watched his father leave before dawn to fix the very trains that carried the region\u2019s workforce and saw his mother navigate a complex web of buses to reach her clients across the Peninsula. Transportation wasn\u2019t an abstract concept; it was the rhythm of his family\u2019s life.\n\nThis fascination led him to UC Berkeley for his undergraduate degree in Urban Studies, followed by a Master's in Transportation Management from San Jos\u00e9 State. He resisted the lure of tech startups, feeling a pull toward public service. The 2008 recession, which hit during his college years, solidified his desire for a stable career improving the systems people relied on. He joined the San Francisco Municipal Transportation Agency (SFMTA) as a junior planner and meticulously worked his way up.\n\nA key turning point was his successful project optimizing the Muni Metro T Third Street line. It was more than data and logistics; he felt he was improving the daily lives of people in neighborhoods like the ones he grew up near. Now, as a Senior Transportation Planner, his days are a mix of data analysis, community meetings, and long-term strategic planning from his office near City Hall.\n\nNikolai lives his work. He resides in a rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond, a 3.8-mile MUNI ride from his office. His daily commute is a field study. He lives with his long-term partner, Clara, a landscape architect, and their shared passion for well-designed public spaces fuels many of their conversations. Weekends are for cycling through Golden Gate Park, exploring the dim sum spots on Clement Street, and quiet evenings at home.\n\nHis greatest aspiration is to spearhead a major project\u2014perhaps a new Bus Rapid Transit corridor or a significant expansion of the subway system\u2014that fundamentally reshapes how San Franciscans move. For Nikolai, the city isn't just a map of streets; it's a living organism, and he has dedicated his life to ensuring its arteries flow smoothly and equitably for everyone."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was eight when his father took him to the Daly City BART yard. The air smelled of ozone and hot metal. Standing beside a train carriage, its massive wheels towering over him, he felt a profound awe. He saw his father not as just a mechanic, but as a guardian of these rumbling metal giants. That day, the abstract idea of transit became a tangible, powerful force in his life, cementing a fascination not with the destination, but with the journey itself and the people who make it possible.\n\n2.\nDuring his sophomore year at Berkeley, around 2008, he saw a foreclosure sign on the lawn of a friend's family home in San Pablo. The sight hit him with a cold, visceral dread\u2014a feeling of systemic failure. The risky promise of tech startups suddenly felt hollow and frivolous. He craved stability, not just for himself, but as a public good. That raw moment of economic anxiety hardened his resolve to build a career in public service, creating systems that anchor people\u2019s lives, rather than gamble with them.\n\n3.\nYears later, standing anonymously at a T Third stop in the Bayview, he watched his project in action. He saw a woman balancing grocery bags easily make a train she would have missed before his schedule optimization. A quiet, fierce pride washed over him. The data points on his screen had transformed into tangible relief for a real person, saving them precious minutes. That moment affirmed his purpose: his work wasn't about logistics, but about giving people back moments of their lives.\n\n4.\nOn his first real date with Clara, they walked through Salesforce Park. As she talked about the resilient plant life, he found himself explaining the intricate bus ramp design of the Transit Center below. He saw her face light up with genuine curiosity, not polite boredom. In that moment, he felt a thrilling sense of being understood. His professional obsession wasn't a niche quirk; it was a language of seeing the world that he could finally share completely with someone he loved.\n\n5.\nJust last week, on his daily 38R MUNI ride home, he watched the \"regular\" passengers: a cook from a Clement Street restaurant, a student with a portfolio case, an elderly woman with her rolling cart. He felt a deep, abiding sense of responsibility. These weren't statistics; they were his neighbors, their routines inextricably linked to the decisions made in his office. The mundane commute was a constant, humbling reminder of the human lives that form the true map of his city."
